answer: The table presents the results of adversarial training with different numbers of adversarial examples (k) in the minibatch, as examined in a paper published at ICLR 2017. The adversarial examples were generated using the step l.l. method. The table shows the accuracy of the model in handling both clean and adversarial images. When k = 16, the model demonstrates a good trade-off between accuracy on clean images (77.6%) and adversarial images (75.3%). This is because, as k increases, the model becomes more robust against adversarial attacks, but its performance on clean images decreases. Conversely, as k decreases, the model's performance on clean images improves, but its robustness against adversarial attacks decreases.
